06287nam a22007695i 9781477312513DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212017txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773125137 a10.7560/3124902doi  a(DE-B1597)588091  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aLIT0170002bisacsh00aMake Ours Marvel :bMedia Convergence and a Comics Universe /ced. by Matt Yockey. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Excelsior! Or, Everything Th at Rises Must Converge -- tChapter 1. Reforming the “Justice” System. Marvel’s Avengers and the Transformation of the All-Star Team Book -- tChapter 2. Man Without Fear. David Mack, Daredevil, and the “Bounds of Diff erence” in Superhero Comics -- tChapter 3. “This Female Fights Back!” A Feminist History of Marvel Comics -- tChapter 4. “Share Your Universe”. Generation, Gender, and the Future of Marvel Publishing -- tChapter 5. Breaking Brand 164 From NuMarvel to MarvelNOW! Marvel Comics in the Age of Media Convergence -- tChapter 6. Marvel and the Form of Motion Comics -- tChapter 7. Transmedia Storytelling in the “Marvel Cinematic Universe” and the Logics of Convergence-Era Popular Seriality -- tChapter 8. The Marvel One-Shots and Transmedia Storytelling -- tChapter 9. Spinning Webs Constructing Authors, Genre, and Fans in the Spider-Man Film Franchise -- tChapter 10. Playing Peter Parker Spider-Man and Superhero Film Performance -- tChapter 11. Spotting Stan 297 Th e Fun and Function of Stan Lee’s Cameos in the Marvel Universe(s) -- tchapter 12. Schrödinger’s Cape The Quantum Seriality of the Marvel Multiverse -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe creation of the Fantastic Four effectively launched the Marvel Comics brand in 1961. Within ten years, the introduction (or reintroduction) of characters such as Spider-Man, the Hulk, Iron Man, Captain America, and the X-Men catapulted Marvel past its primary rival, DC Comics, for domination of the comic book market. Since the 2000s, the company’s iconic characters have leaped from page to screens with the creation of the Marvel Cinematic Universe, which includes everything from live-action film franchises of Iron Man and the Avengers to television and streaming media, including the critically acclaimed Netflix series Daredevil and Jessica Jones. Marvel, now owned by Disney, has clearly found the key to transmedia success. Make Ours Marvel traces the rise of the Marvel brand and its transformation into a transmedia empire over the past fifty years. A dozen original essays range across topics such as how Marvel expanded the notion of an all-star team book with The Avengers, which provided a roadmap for the later films, to the company’s attempts to create lasting female characters and readerships, to its regular endeavors to reinvigorate its brand while still maintaining the stability that fans crave. Demonstrating that the secret to Marvel’s success comes from adeptly crossing media boundaries while inviting its audience to participate in creating Marvel’s narrative universe, this book shows why the company and its characters will continue to influence storytelling and transmedia empire building for the foreseeable future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aMotion pictures and comic books. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comics & Graphic Novels.2bisacsh1 aBrinker, Felix, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilmore, James N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraves, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc